   GLOBAL FIX: To prevent this class of bug, developers should follow the rule
   of "owning" pointers:
   1.  Always set a pointer to `NULL` immediately after calling `free(pointer)`.
   This ensures that any subsequent attempts to use the pointer will result in a
   predictable null pointer dereference (which is easier to debug) rather than
   an exploitable use-after-free.
   2.  Use static analysis tools (like Clang Static Analyzer or
   AddressSanitizer) during build time and development to catch dangling pointer
   usage.
   3.  In modern C++, utilize smart pointers (`std::unique_ptr`,
   `std::shared_ptr`) which manage object lifetime automatically and eliminate
   manual `malloc`/`free` or `new`/`delete` risks.
